{
  "text": "The GO on the worn surface was confirmed by the Raman spectra analysis of the two most intense features of the D band (1345 cm −1 ) and G band (1587 cm −1 ) as shown in Figure 10b . Similar to the graphene nanofluids lubricated surface, the GO on the worn surface also presented the strengthening of the intensity ratio of I D /I G , in contrast that of the pristine GO powder. This should not be a surprise considering that those flakes were lying in between the two sliding surfaces standing a pressure of several hundred MPa. Such phenomenon has been well documented in the previous reports [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . graphene nanofluids lubricated surface, the GO on the worn surface also presented the strengthening of the intensity ratio of ID/IG, in contrast that of the pristine GO powder. This should not be a surprise considering that those flakes were lying in between the two sliding surfaces standing a pressure of several hundred MPa. Such phenomenon has been well documented in the previous reports [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
